  "text": "Log retention policy enforcement in Apache Kafka is implemented across multiple Java source files in the sg-evals/kafka--0753c489 repository. The enforcement chain operates as follows:\n\n**Configuration Definition:** Log retention parameters are defined in ServerLogConfigs.java (LOG_RETENTION_TIME_MILLIS_CONFIG at line 57, LOG_RETENTION_BYTES_CONFIG at line 64, LOG_CLEANUP_INTERVAL_MS_CONFIG at line 68) and TopicConfig.java (RETENTION_MS_CONFIG at line 75, RETENTION_BYTES_CONFIG at line 66). Remote storage-specific retention configs are defined in RemoteLogManagerConfig.java.\n\n**Configuration Validation:** KafkaConfig.scala (line 508) validates that log.retention.ms must be either -1 (unlimited) or >= 1. LogConfig.java implements comprehensive validation: validateRemoteStorageRetentionTime() (line 595) ensures local retention time doesn't exceed global retention time, validateRemoteStorageRetentionSize() (line 578) ensures local retention size doesn't exceed global retention size, and validateRemoteStorageRequiresDeleteCleanupPolicy() (line 570) enforces delete cleanup policy for remote storage. DynamicBrokerConfig.scala provides dynamic validation with validateLogLocalRetentionMs() (line 664) and validateLogLocalRetentionBytes() (line 679) for runtime configuration updates.\n\n**Segment Deletion Enforcement:** The primary enforcement mechanism is in UnifiedLog.java. The deleteOldSegments() method (line 1894) orchestrates deletion by calling deleteLogStartOffsetBreachedSegments(), deleteRetentionSizeBreachedSegments() (line 1946), and deleteRetentionMsBreachedSegments() (line 1908). These methods use helper methods localRetentionMs() (line 2646) and localRetentionSize() (line 2650) to compute effective retention values, accounting for both local and remote storage configurations.\n\n**Time-based Retention:** deleteRetentionMsBreachedSegments() (lines 1908-1943) implements time-based deletion by comparing segment timestamps against retention time thresholds. It uses a DeletionCondition that checks if startMs - segment.largestTimestamp() > retentionMs, triggering deletion of segments beyond the retention window.\n\n**Size-based Retention:** deleteRetentionSizeBreachedSegments() (lines 1946-1974) implements size-based deletion by tracking cumulative size and deleting segments when the log size exceeds the retention limit. It uses an AtomicLong to maintain the remaining breached size and deletes segments until the log size falls below the threshold.\n\n**Periodic Cleanup Execution:** LogManager.scala's cleanupLogs() method (line 1380) implements the periodic cleanup thread. It runs at intervals defined by LOG_CLEANUP_INTERVAL_MS_CONFIG and calls log.deleteOldSegments() (line 1404) for each partition, coordinating with the log cleaner to prevent concurrent modification.\n\n**Remote Log Retention:** RemoteLogManager.java implements retention for remote storage through RemoteLogRetentionHandler (line 1116). The handler contains isSegmentBreachedByRetentionTime() (line 1154) and isSegmentBreachedByRetentionSize() (line 1131) methods that check remote segments against retention policies. The cleanupExpiredRemoteLogSegments() method (line 1224) orchestrates deletion of expired remote segments based on both time and size retention breaches.\n\nThe enforcement operates in a coordinated manner: configuration validation ensures valid retention parameters are set, the LogManager periodically triggers cleanup, and UnifiedLog enforces both time-based and size-based deletion policies on local segments while RemoteLogManager handles remote segment retention independently."
}

